{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fba61a37-1535-4fd2-ac99-9a4b34fa10fe","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01VNoCh86J89NeT3yGMmctkq","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_017xUuLex4U4qPdgBJF4EFxs","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-42b276f01aa6495db756b117c322169e && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with blame-crash for crash dump collection","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with blame-crash for crash dump collection"}],"interactionId":"f38f0dc5-56d7-4a37-8fa1-adb9b0b999da","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run the tests with `dotnet test` and collect a crash dump if any test crashes the host process. \n\nFor .NET, the way to collect crash dumps on test host crashes is to use environment variables that configure the .NET runtime's crash dump collection. The key environment variables are:\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` — enables mini dump collection on crash\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` — full dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=<path>` — where to write the dump\n\n\n- \nActually, there's a more straightforward approach using the `--blame-crash` flag built into `dotnet test`. This tells the test platform to automatically capture a crash dump if the test host process exits unexpectedly, and I can further customize it with `--blame-crash-dump-type` to specify the dump format or `--blame-crash-collect-always` to ensure collection happens.","outputTokens":482,"requestId":"0835:381EF2:C695A1:E75FE5:69EAC5D3"},"id":"73308603-e8f1-4ea5-acc7-14a935617203","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:22:37.804Z","parentId":"56d86149-d6a4-408a-8a3a-cbce07c06fdf"}
